Sense of coherence (SOC) is a psychological factor that contributes to mental
health maintenance under stressful environment. Likewise, level of SOC might
affect mental health among healthcare workers during the COVID-19 pandemic
differently. In this study, we investigated the relationships between lifestyle
changes and mental health (General Health Questionnaire-12: GHQ-12) among
different level of SOC (weak, moderate, or strong by SOC-13). The data of 898
healthcare workers from cross-sectional survey dataset were extracted and
analyzed. As results, based on GHQ-12 score, 86.1% of 244 participants with weak 
SOC, 60.1% of 606 participants with moderate SOC, and 31.3% of 48 participants
with strong SOC had poor mental health. Both SOC levels and lifestyle changes
(except alcohol consumption) had significant main effects on the GHQ-12 score.
