question of loneliness, the Social Provisions Scale, Sense of Coherence Scale,
and Geriatric Depression Scale. Scores on Groll's index (p = .02) and the Sense
of Coherence Scale (p = .04) were positively correlated with loneliness and
negatively correlated with geriatric depression (p = .001). Having a diagnosis of
cancer, social support, and age were not correlated with loneliness 6 years from 
baseline. Loneliness did not change during the 6 years of follow-up, and symptoms
of depression and the sense of coherence appeared to be important components of
loneliness. Finally, having a diagnosis of cancer and social support were not
associated with loneliness.

