Borderline personality disorder (BPD) is a severe psychiatric condition that is
associated with functional impairment and pathological traits. It has been argued
that identity impairment is one of the core features of BPD, which can be
manifested in different ways, including fragmented autobiographical narratives.
Here, we considered both the traditional and modern conceptualizations of BPD to 
examine the relation between identity impairment, as operationalized through
autobiographical memory, and features of BPD. We hypothesized that BPD features
would be associated with higher levels of fragmentation in narrative identity,
narrative intimacy, and narrative coherence in participants' autobiographical
memory. To test this hypothesis, we recruited 298 university students who were
administered a series of self-report measures of BPD and were asked to describe
an autobiographical memory about a turning point in their lives. Narrative
identity, but not narrative intimacy nor coherence, was the dominant predictor of
BPD features. We discuss our findings in terms of how individuals with features
of BPD struggle with many aspects of a distorted sense of self. (PsycInfo
