Most studies about infant and young child feeding (IYCF) practices are often
perceived as an individual choice depending on mothers' or caregivers' knowledge 
or attitudes and are focused on mothers' failure rather than successes in
adequately feeding their children. However, the role of life course experiences
in IYCF is less investigated. Applying a Salutogenic Model of Health, this study 
on 14 mothers looks at women's life course learning experiences shaping
appropriate IYCF practices during the first year of child's life in a rural
district of Rwanda. Transcripts from in-depth interviews were analysed using
thematic analysis. Results indicate that positive social interaction with parents
or grandmothers during childhood such as sharing meals, parental role models for 
dietary choices and cooking skills gained by participating in household food
preparation played a role in shaping appropriate IYCF practices. Negative
experiences during childhood also had a positive influence on IYCF practices for 
some participants by converting life course constraints into learning
opportunities. Motherhood increased mothers' sense of responsibility over their
children's health and nutrition. Moreover, mothers' participation in community
cooking classes and role modelling approach were strong avenues that enabled
their learning through positive interactions and encouragement. Nutrition
promotion interventions should consider tailoring nutrition advice to the
complexity of mothers' life course experiences by creating opportunities for
positive learning experiences of appropriate IYCF practices.

